        "created_at": "2026-02-13T16:15:03.634Z",
        "cooked": "<p>The future of messaging/communication</p>\n<p>Hey all, I believe that Signal Messenger can be the answer to the cross-platform messaging problem that is as old as the Internet itself, while being completely secure and free from exploitation by outside influences.</p>\n<p>This is a worldwide problem, and I admit I am coming from the perspective of the US user.</p>\n<p>Here in the US, Apple‚Äôs products are extremely prevalent.  After years of practice and training, I‚Äôve managed to get my family ‚Äì a mix of iPhones and Samsung Galaxy devices ‚Äì all on Signal.<br>\nThis has become our daily communication platform.  Video calls are easy and frequent across iOS and Android devices.<br>\nHowever, as the Apple device users still use Facetime calling for their iOS friends, it‚Äôs become a good perspective to see what features Signal is missing that keeps it from being the easy, go-to, messenger of choice.  If Signal is as easy and usable as ‚ÄúFacetime‚Äù, getting people onto it is vastly easier, and is a huge win for security and cross-platform functionality.</p>\n<p>Functionallly, group calls are the most dramatic feature that we need to build parity in.  Adding people to a ‚ÄúFacetime‚Äù call is so simple that young children do it with ease.  I see my niece in a group call with 3 of her 7-year old friends ALL THE TIME.<br>\nSetting up groups and then calling is a user interface nightmare when you are trying to coordinate impatient people.<br>\nThe ability to add people to ongoing calls quickly and easily is <em>essential</em> to be the dominant messaging platform.</p>\n<p>From a user experience/design point-of-view, Signal actually has tons of great features and functionality that I rely on.<br>\nTo make it easier for those who are less‚Ä¶technically-inclined‚Ä¶ to use though, we should lean into hinting/prompting in the user interface when some actions are <em>likely</em>.<br>\nFor example, my dad video calls me with Signal, but either accidentally (or by default) his camera is disabled.  A simple slow swirl around the camera button would hint him to push it to get the camera enabled.  As-is, I have to sort of try and describe/walk through buttons to get him to push it.   This user experience can be vastly improved.<br>\nA slow swirl around the perimeter of the camera button when you are in a video call and your camera is DISABLED.  This enhances accessibility by enabling the user to see which functions are disabled but likely to be used.<br>\nSame thing for mute ‚Äì if you are in a call and are muted, the mute button should have a slow, moving swirl around it to draw attention.</p>\n<p>I believe that Signal is the best option for communication, and making it EASY for people to use; smoothing out the small niggling pieces and bumps to make it much easier to adopt and spread.</p>",
